<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="478" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,994,1400]" box="[151,1435,994,1016]" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,994,1016]" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
1- Antenna with segments robust and thick (
<figureCitation box="[624,678,994,1016]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="4.[151,262,1992,2015]" captionTargetBox="[347,1241,1425,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[340,1247,1420,1972]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Dorsal views of (7) Merragata hebroides, (8 Lipogomphus lacuniferus, (9) Hebrus engaeus. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457971/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Fig.7</figureCitation>
); segment IV subequal in length to segment I.......... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="White" authorityYear="1877" box="[1232,1435,994,1015]" class="Insecta" family="Hebridae" genus="Merragata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="478" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hebroides">
<emphasis box="[1232,1435,994,1015]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Merragata hebroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,994,1400]" box="[151,1435,1023,1045]" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1023,1045]" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
- Antenna with segments slender; segment IV longer than segment I (
<figureCitation box="[876,944,1023,1045]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–5" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1959,1982]" captionTargetBox="[357,1230,1285,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[340,1247,1251,1949]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 3–5. Hebrus alvearensis sp. nov., male, holotype: (3) lateral view of right buccula; (4) dorsal view of right antenna, (5) paramere of male genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457969/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[954,967,1023,1045]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="4.[151,262,1992,2015]" captionTargetBox="[347,1241,1425,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[340,1247,1420,1972]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Dorsal views of (7) Merragata hebroides, (8 Lipogomphus lacuniferus, (9) Hebrus engaeus. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457971/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">8</figureCitation>
)..................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,994,1400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
<keyLead pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
2- Antennal segment IV without constriction (
<figureCitation box="[641,699,1052,1074]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="4.[151,262,1992,2015]" captionTargetBox="[347,1241,1425,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[340,1247,1420,1972]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Dorsal views of (7) Merragata hebroides, (8 Lipogomphus lacuniferus, (9) Hebrus engaeus. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457971/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); male with a subapical spine on the posterior surface of the hind tibia..................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berg" authorityYear="1879" box="[1191,1435,1082,1103]" class="Insecta" family="Hebridae" genus="Lipogomphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="478" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacuniferus">
<emphasis box="[1191,1435,1082,1103]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Lipogomphus lacuniferus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,994,1400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
<keyLead pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
- Antennal IV segment with a constriction in the middle (false membranous articulation), so that the antenna appears to possess five segments (
<figureCitation box="[370,429,1140,1162]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–5" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1959,1982]" captionTargetBox="[357,1230,1285,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[340,1247,1251,1949]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 3–5. Hebrus alvearensis sp. nov., male, holotype: (3) lateral view of right buccula; (4) dorsal view of right antenna, (5) paramere of male genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457969/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); male lacking a subapical spine on the posterior surface of the hind tibia (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curtis" authorityYear="1833" box="[1145,1216,1141,1162]" class="Insecta" family="Hebridae" genus="Hebrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="478" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1145,1216,1141,1162]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Hebrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)................ 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,994,1400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
<keyLead pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
3- Body length approximately 3.00 mm; bucculae brownish, ventrally straight and subsequently slightly concave; clavus marked on each side with a small, basal, whitish spot adjacent to metanotal elevation and without pale spots on the membrane (
<figureCitation box="[1365,1423,1199,1221]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="4.[151,262,1992,2015]" captionTargetBox="[347,1241,1425,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[340,1247,1420,1972]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Dorsal views of (7) Merragata hebroides, (8 Lipogomphus lacuniferus, (9) Hebrus engaeus. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457971/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Metanotal elevation with lateral and hind margins carinate, with prominent median carina sharply obliquely narrowed on sides along apical two-fifths..................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Drake and Chapman" authorityYear="1958" box="[1274,1430,1258,1279]" class="Insecta" family="Hebridae" genus="Hebrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="478" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="engaeus">
<emphasis box="[1274,1430,1258,1279]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Hebrus engaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,994,1400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
<keyLead pageId="4" pageNumber="478">
- Body length between 1.84 and 
<quantity box="[521,608,1287,1309]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" pageId="4" pageNumber="478" unit="mm" value="1.95">1.95 mm</quantity>
; bucculae yellowish, ventrally curved, posteriorly conical and slightly elevated; clavus with a pearl-white marking from the base until almost to the apex of the metanotal elevation (3/4 distance) and four distinct whitish spots on the membrane (
<figureCitation box="[539,632,1346,1368]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1155,1178]" captionTargetBox="[355,1233,488,1125]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[340,1247,483,1132]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (1) Hebrus alvearensis sp. nov. dorsal view, female paratype; (2) Hebrus alvearensis sp. nov. dorsal view, male holotype. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457967/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Figs. 1, 2</figureCitation>
). Metanotal elevation with raised edges and strong, straight median carina, flanked by two submedial depressions....................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Stella &amp; Pall, 2018" authorityName="Stella &amp; Pall" authorityYear="2018" box="[1164,1352,1378,1399]" class="Insecta" family="Hebridae" genus="Hebrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="478" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alvearensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1164,1352,1378,1399]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">Hebrus alvearensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1359,1436,1378,1400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="478" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1359,1436,1378,1400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="478">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</subSubSection>
